 Let us extend the coordinate change 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\phi,z)\mapsto\left(q_{1},q_{2},q_{3}\right)$
\end_inset

 to a canonical coordinate change
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(q_{1},q_{2},q_{3},p_{1},p_{2},p_{3}\right)\mapsto\left(\phi,r,q_{3},p_{\phi},p_{r},p_{z}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where we denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{r},p_{\phi},p_{z}$
\end_inset

 momenta variables corresponding to new coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $(r,\phi,z)$
\end_inset

.
 In fact, we need only the coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\phi}$
\end_inset

 which is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\phi}=-p_{1}q_{2}+q_{1}p_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the function 
\begin_inset Formula $-p_{1}q_{2}+p_{2}q_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the first integral.
 It is called 
\shape italic
the angular momentum around the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{3}$
\end_inset

-axis
\shape default
.
